{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619993"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:38:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16600"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16600"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.56,0.04,0.19,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9291"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75994"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9291"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61495"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5324"},{"type":"tags","id":"10146"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22045"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75994"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMifepristone is a medication used in medical termination of pregnancy. It is typically administered before prostaglandin analogues.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of mifepristone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits progesterone synthesis","Competitively antagonises progesterone receptors","Activates oestrogen receptors","Directly stimulates myometrial contractions","Induces prostaglandin synthesis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMifepristone functions as a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitive antagonist at progesterone receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. It competes with and displaces endogenous progesterone from its receptors due to having a higher binding affinity. When progesterone signalling is blocked, the endometrial lining begins to break down and the cervix softens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other proposed mechanisms are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits progesterone synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: mifepristone does not interfere with the production of progesterone, only its receptor binding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivates oestrogen receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: mifepristone specifically targets progesterone receptors and has minimal interaction with oestrogen pathways\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly stimulates myometrial contractions\u003C/strong\u003E: any contractile effects are secondary to the loss of progesterone signalling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduces prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: while prostaglandins like misoprostol are often given after mifepristone, this is not how mifepristone itself works\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anti-progesterone effects lead to pregnancy termination by creating an environment that cannot sustain the developing embryo.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mifepristone acts as a competitive antagonist at progesterone receptors, blocking the effects of progesterone.","Mifepristone has higher binding affinity for progesterone receptors than endogenous progesterone.","By blocking progesterone action, mifepristone causes endometrial breakdown and cervical softening."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Termination of pregnancy. Queensland Health. Updated September 2024. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0029/735293/g-top.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61495"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16600"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61495"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T20:48:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T20:49:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9291"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75994"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remem